      # Many outliers are observed in the given dataset

      Many outliers are observed in the given dataset¶

      #  Let us Minimize the outliers by replacing by median
      . . .
      In [43]:
       
      for col_name in df.drop(columns = 'Pass/Fail').columns:
          q1 = df[col_name].quantile(0.25)
          q3 = df[col_name].quantile(0.75)
          iqr = q3 - q1
          low = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
          high = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
          df.loc[(df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > high), col_name] = df[col_name].median()
      . . .

      # RandomForest Model with downsample data

      RandomForest Model with downsample data¶

      In [71]:
       
      from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
      from sklearn import metrics
      model_downsample_rf = RandomForestClassifier()
      model_downsample_rf.fit(X_train_ds, y_train_ds.values.ravel())
      y_pred_ds_rf = model_downsample_rf.predict(X_test_ds)
      model_downsample_rf_score_tr = model_downsample_rf.score(X_train_ds, y_train_ds)
      print(model_downsample_rf_score_tr)
      model_downsample_rf_score = model_downsample_rf.score(X_test_ds, y_test_ds)
      print(model_downsample_rf_score)
      cfm_ds = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test_ds, y_pred_ds_rf)
      cl_ds_report = metrics.classification_report(y_test_ds, y_pred_ds_rf)
      print(cfm_ds)
      print(cl_ds_report)

      In [72]:
       
      # Train data and Test data scores are NOT comparable, train data score more than the test data
      # Hence, it comes under underfitting scenario
      # With respect to subject of the problem, predicting the fail correctly is more important than the predicting the pass correctly.
      # Hence, recall from the classification report will be playing the vital role here
      # let us build the model with cross validation to understand whether it can resolve the issue
      . . .

      from scipy.stats import randint as sp_randint
      # specify parameters and distributions to sample from

                    "max_features": sp_randint(1, 11),
                    "min_samples_split": sp_randint(2, 11),
                    "min_samples_leaf": sp_randint(1, 11),
                    "bootstrap": [True, False],
                    "criterion": ["gini", "entropy"]}

      from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
      from sklearn import metrics
      model_upsample_lr = LogisticRegression(solver='saga',multi_class="ovr",max_iter=5000)
      model_upsample_lr.fit(X_train_us, y_train_us)
      y_pred_us_lr = model_upsample_lr.predict(X_test_us)
      model_upsample_lr_score_tr = model_upsample_lr.score(X_train_us, y_train_us)
      model_upsample_lr_score = model_upsample_lr.score(X_test_us, y_test_us)
      print(model_upsample_lr_score_tr)
      print(model_upsample_lr_score)
      cfm_us_lr = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test_us, y_pred_us_lr)
      cl_us_lr_report = metrics.classification_report(y_test_us, y_pred_us_lr)
      print(cfm_us_lr)
      print(cl_us_lr_report)

      from sklearn.svm import SVC
      model_upsample_svc = SVC(kernel = 'linear', gamma ='scale', C = 1)
      model_upsample_svc.fit(X_train_us, y_train_us)
      model_upsample_svc_score_tr = model_upsample_svc.score(X_train_us, y_train_us)
      model_upsample_svc_score = model_upsample_svc.score(X_test_us, y_test_us)
      y_pred_us_svc = model_upsample_svc.predict(X_test_us)
      print(model_upsample_svc_score)
      print(model_upsample_svc_score_tr)
      cfm_us_svc = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test_us, y_pred_us_svc)
      cl_us_svc_report = metrics.classification_report(y_test_us, y_pred_us_svc)

      print(cl_us_svc_report)

      # Findings after applying PCA on the dataset
      We can see that the first 150 components explain more
      than 95% of variation.

      components. Therefore we can drop 151th component

      Findings after applying PCA on the dataset¶

      We can see that the first 150 components explain more than 95% of variation. Between first 150 components, more than 95% of the information is captured. The above plot shows almost 95% variance by the first 150 components. Therefore we can drop 151th component onwards.

      # Final Model
          - Different model built with downsample and upsample data
          - Optimize the parameters with CV and hyperparameter tuning
          - Underfit is removed from the model using upsample data using SMOTE
          - Predict the fail is more important than predict the pass with respect to the problem statement
          - Model with downsample data is not performed better when compared to upsample data
          - Hence upsample will be used for the final model
          - All the model with upsample data are performed well with respect to our problem statement.
          - Recall score for predicting the fail is good 
          - Any model with CV and hyperparameter tuning can be selected for the final model
          - Here we have selected SVC model for the pickling since SVM is relatively memory efficient

      Final Model¶

      - Different model built with downsample and upsample data
- Optimize the parameters with CV and hyperparameter tuning
- Underfit is removed from the model using upsample data using SMOTE
- Predict the fail is more important than predict the pass with respect to the problem statement
- Model with downsample data is not performed better when compared to upsample data
- Hence upsample will be used for the final model
- All the model with upsample data are performed well with respect to our problem statement.
- Recall score for predicting the fail is good 
- Any model with CV and hyperparameter tuning can be selected for the final model
- Here we have selected SVC model for the pickling.

      # Function for preprocess the future data

      Function for preprocess the future data¶

      In [162]:
       
      future_preprocess = pd.DataFrame()
      def future_prediction(input_data):
          global DB
          import pandas as pd
          future_preprocess=future_df.drop('Time',axis=1)
          print(future_preprocess.shape)
          constant_value_columns = [
              '5', '13', '42', '49', '52', '69', '97', '141', '149', '178', '179', '186', '189', '190',
              '191', '192', '193', '194', '226', '229', '230', '231', '232', '233', '234', '235', '236',
              '237', '240', '241', '242', '243', '256', '257', '258', '259', '260', '261', '262', '263',
              '264', '265', '266', '276', '284', '313', '314', '315', '322', '325', '326', '327', '328',
              '329', '330', '364', '369', '370', '371', '372', '373', '374', '375', '378', '379', '380',
              '381', '394', '395', '396', '397', '398', '399', '400', '401', '402', '403', '404', '414',
              '422', '449', '450', '451', '458', '461', '462', '463', '464', '465', '466', '481', '498',
              '501', '502', '503', '504', '505', '506', '507', '508', '509', '512', '513', '514', '515',
              '528', '529', '530', '531', '532', '533', '534', '535', '536', '537', '538'
              ]
          future_preprocess = future_preprocess.drop(constant_value_columns,axis=1)
          print(future_preprocess.shape)
      #
          future_preprocess=future_preprocess.replace(np.NaN, 0)
      #
          for col_name in future_preprocess.columns:
              q1 = future_preprocess[col_name].quantile(0.25)
              q3 = future_preprocess[col_name].quantile(0.75)
              iqr = q3 - q1
              low = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
              high = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
              future_preprocess.loc[(future_preprocess[col_name] < low) | (future_preprocess[col_name] > high), col_name] = future_preprocess[col_name].median()
      #
          print(future_preprocess.shape)
          DB = future_preprocess
      . . .

      future_prediction(future_df)

      # Few points about semiconductor manufacturing environment:

      Few points about semiconductor manufacturing environment:¶

       
          # The semiconductor manufacturing environment is a high volume manufacturing environment.
          # Data taken during manufacturing is available from a variety of sources.
          # The semiconductor industry is one of the most capitalintensive industries with a high of capital investment on equipment. 
          # A good classification prediction model is beneficial for the prediction in semiconductor manufacturing fabrication process. 
          # Most semiconductor manufacturing is highly complex and has produced constantly hundreds of metrology data that are awaiting for process engineers to analyze for the purpose of maintaining efficient operations and getting optimum yield of high quality products.

      # Conclusion on the results:

      Conclusion on the results:¶

       
      # Most of the model with CV and hyperparameter using upsample data are performed well
      # Objective to build a classifier to predict the Pass/Fail yield of a particular process entity and analyse whether all the features are required to build the model or not
      # Many of the features are dropped from the model, hence we can say that all the features are not required to predict the results from the given dataset
      # Predict the fail correctly is very important, yield for in house line testing. 
      # All the classifier model are performed better, here we chose SVC model as the final model, because 
          - SVM works relatively well when there is a clear margin of separation between classes. 
          - SVM is more effective in high dimensional spaces.SVM is relatively memory efficient.
          - SVM is relatively memory efficient.

      Keyboard shortcuts

      The Jupyter Notebook has two different keyboard input modes. Edit mode allows you to type code or text into a cell and is indicated by a green cell border. Command mode binds the keyboard to notebook level commands and is indicated by a grey cell border with a blue left margin.

      Command Mode (press Esc to enable)

      F : find and replace
      Ctrl-Shift-F : open the command palette
      Ctrl-Shift-P : open the command palette
      Enter : enter edit mode
      P : open the command palette
      Shift-Enter : run cell, select below
      Ctrl-Enter : run selected cells
      Alt-Enter : run cell and insert below
      Y : change cell to code
      M : change cell to markdown
      R : change cell to raw
      1 : change cell to heading 1
      2 : change cell to heading 2
      3 : change cell to heading 3
      4 : change cell to heading 4
      5 : change cell to heading 5
      6 : change cell to heading 6
      K : select cell above
      Up : select cell above
      Down : select cell below
      J : select cell below
      Shift-K : extend selected cells above
      Shift-Up : extend selected cells above
      Shift-Down : extend selected cells below
      Shift-J : extend selected cells below
      Ctrl-A : select all cells
      A : insert cell above
      B : insert cell below
      X : cut selected cells
      C : copy selected cells
      Shift-V : paste cells above
      V : paste cells below
      Z : undo cell deletion
      D,D : delete selected cells
      Shift-M : merge selected cells, or current cell with cell below if only one cell is selected
      Ctrl-S : Save and Checkpoint
      S : Save and Checkpoint
      L : toggle line numbers
      O : toggle output of selected cells
      Shift-O : toggle output scrolling of selected cells
      H : show keyboard shortcuts
      I,I : interrupt the kernel
      0,0 : restart the kernel (with dialog)
      Esc : close the pager
      Q : close the pager
      Shift-L : toggles line numbers in all cells, and persist the setting
      Shift-Space : scroll notebook up
      Space : scroll notebook down

      Edit Mode (press Enter to enable)

      Tab : code completion or indent
      Shift-Tab : tooltip
      Ctrl-] : indent
      Ctrl-[ : dedent
      Ctrl-A : select all
      Ctrl-Z : undo
      Ctrl-/ : comment
      Ctrl-D : delete whole line
      Ctrl-U : undo selection
      Insert : toggle overwrite flag
      Ctrl-Home : go to cell start
      Ctrl-Up : go to cell start
      Ctrl-End : go to cell end
      Ctrl-Down : go to cell end
      Ctrl-Left : go one word left
      Ctrl-Right : go one word right
      Ctrl-Backspace : delete word before
      Ctrl-Delete : delete word after
      Ctrl-Y : redo
      Alt-U : redo selection
      Ctrl-M : enter command mode
      Ctrl-Shift-F : open the command palette
      Ctrl-Shift-P : open the command palette
      Esc : enter command mode
